      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I was just using the goblin analogy to try to make the explanation more relatable and engaging. You don't need to worry about goblins, I promise!\n\nTo answer your question, it's likely that the squealing noise is related to the brake pads or rotors. If the brake pads are worn down, it can cause the metal to vibrate and produce a high-pitched squeal. The rotors, on the other hand, can also be the culprit if they're warped or excessively worn, causing the brake pads to vibrate and squeal.\n\nIn your case, since the noise is coming from the front passenger side, it's possible that the brake pads or rotors on that side are the source of the problem. I'd recommend having a professional mechanic inspect the brakes and rotors to determine the root cause of the noise. They can check the brake pad thickness, rotor surface, and other components to give you a more accurate diagnosis.\n\nIt's also possible that the noise is related to the brake caliper or other components, but brake pads and rotors are the most common culprits for high-pitched squealing sounds.",
