      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You can try to gather some clues without taking the wheel off. When it comes to brake pads, you can check the thickness by looking at the pad's wear indicator. Most brake pads have a small metal wear indicator that's exposed when the pad is worn down to a certain thickness. If the pad is worn down to the metal, it's likely time to replace it.\n\nAs for rotors, you can check the surface for excessive wear or scoring. Look for any signs of uneven wear, such as a \"cupped\" or \"warped\" surface. You can also check the rotor's thickness by using a caliper to measure the rotor's diameter.\n\nIn terms of listening, you can try to identify the source of the squeal by listening to the sound. If the squeal is coming from the brake pads, it's usually a high-pitched, sharp sound that's most noticeable when you're applying the brakes. If the squeal is coming from the rotors, it's often a deeper, more rumbling sound that's more noticeable when you're accelerating or decelerating.\n\nIt's worth noting that a good mechanic can often diagnose the issue just by listening to the sound and doing a visual inspection. They can also use",
